SHS National Honor Society
April 27 at 3:27 PM ¬∑

Sunray NHS Member Spotlight: Senior Vice President Audree Wilson

Audree is always one of the first members to volunteer when anyone needs assistance. Recently, she has been completing outdoor services for others, including moving bricks, cleaning, and other various yard projects!

Audree says one of her favorite service projects is delivering Meals on Wheels to the elderly in town. "I love seeing their bright faces!"

She plans to attend WTAMU in the fall to major in nursing and become a pediatric oncology nurse.

We are thankful to have Audree as a dedicated member of the National Honor Society!

SHS National Honor Society
April 20 at 4:39 PM ¬∑

Sunray NHS Member Spotlight: Senior Yaritza Villareal

If you look closely, you might see one of Yari's projects around town. Yari has been spreading joy and brightness in the community by painting Kindness Rocks. She has placed 55 rocks in the area so far. She has also been grocery shopping for her neighbors and checking on them to see how she can help.

Yari stated her favorite part of school was getting to interact with her classmates and teachers. "We created so many memories in the classrooms, from Connor sitting in a trash can and getting stuck and Michael making homemade lemonade in Mrs. Zerby's room."

Her plans for the future are to attend Amarillo College and transfer to West Texas A&M to major in animal science. "After majoring in animal science, I will then decide if I want to further my education to become a veterinarian."

We are proud to have Yaritza as a member of National Honor Society!

post_text:
MS Parents,

Monday, April 20th from 3-6 pm, we will have locker item pick up. We need all items picked up on Monday. Everything is bagged up in a plastic bag labeled with your student's name. There are several items that were found lying in the hallways, in lockers without names, the gym, etc. Items that do not have names will be placed on the picnic tables spread apart for you to claim. As I bagged up lockers and found items that belonged to the school (library books, dictionaries, athletic clothes, etc.), then I kept them and labeled them with your student's name.

If you have a personal band instrument, we will have those outside too.

If you have items at home that belong to the school, please keep those items somewhere safe. We will make a plan on how we will have you return those items (athletic clothes, library books, classroom books, etc.) at a later date, but please do not throw them away.

I hope you are all well! Please help your student get their work done and communicate with your student's teachers if you need help!

Mrs. Boatmun

shared_text:
SHS National Honor Society
April 14 at 11:23 PM ¬∑

Sunray NHS Member Spotlight: Cayman Ivins

Cayman has been a busy lady! During the past month, she has provided meals for the elderly, cleaned the FFA barn, made 172 face masks and 284 face mask holders for a hospital in Amarillo, and "egged" houses for Easter. She donated over 85 hours of her time serving the community.

She stated her favorite part about community service is seeing the impact she can have on others. "I have been very blessed to be able to help others, so it is very rewarding to see it do good for my community."

Cayman is also involved in playing softball and showing pigs. "These keep me very busy throughout the year, and they are two of the things I am very passionate about."

We are proud to have Cayman as a member of our chapter of the National Honor Society!

post_text:
Congratulations to Aukazia Ortega and Rylee DeBord! They were the first two to submit pictures and a brief description of how they helped a senior. Both SHS Seniors have won $250 in scholarship money.

Seniors there is still good news...
The contest will continue. Each time you send a picture and description of yourself helping a Senior Citizen, you will earn $10 in scholarship money. You can continue to earn until you reach $200. Aukazia and Rylee, you can enter this one, too, which means you could walk away with $450 each!

Students, once you have enrolled in college classes, print your schedule and take it to Sunray ISD's Central Office to request your check.

The first $500 was donated by Mr. Harrison. The remaining will be funded by the Sunray ISD Scholarship Fund. Thank you Mr. Harrison and SISD School Board for supporting our Seniors and Senior Citizens!

Good job to everyone who has submitted entries. Keep up the good work!

COME JOIN US!!!!
Why: Video Challenge
When: Saturday, March 7, 2020
Where: Sunray High School Gym
Time: 3:00 pm ( Please arrive no later than 2:45)

SBAX will be doing their video challenge for an opportunity to compete at Regional Hub Contest in Austin, TX. This challenge is in conjunction with the programs ROADS on Mars (NESSP and Texas Space Grant Consortium) and the launch of Mars 2020 rover in July 2020. They have to video their challenge and score high on their challenge to be invited to Austin, TX for state competition on Saturday, April, 18th. They are competing with teams across Texas! Please come, cheer, and support SBAX on to victory!!!!

post_text:
Sunray held our first Robotics competition last Saturday. We had 29 teams from 11 different schools competing in the 3rd Panhandle Plains North FTC League match of the season. The match was won by Dimmitt. Sunray has 4 teams competing. We finished 15th 19th 21st and 26th for the day. The matches started at 10 am and were finished by 3:30. Each team played 5 matches.

The League Championship will be Feb. 1st at Frank Phillips. This will determine who advances to Regionals, and ultimately UIL State Robotics in Dallas in March.

post_text:
Sunray ISD would like to welcome Jance Morris as the new Middle School Principal to replace Mrs. Keisling, as she will be retiring at the end of this school year.

Jance graduated from Tarleton State University in 2009 with a Bachelor of Science in Kinesiology. He attained his Masters Degree in Education Administration from Lamar University in 2012. Jance served as the Head Boys Basketball coach at Lingleville, Dalhart, Tulia, Perryton, and Odessa High School. He also served as an Assistant Principal at Dalhart Jr. High and currently an Assistant Principal at Odessa High School.

Jance's wife, Marisa, is a Kindergarten teacher. They have two children; Jackson, a 4-year-old, and Lyla, a one-year-old. The Morris spend their free time on the golf course or watching basketball games. We are passionate about educating and serving children, and we are very excited to be Bobcats!

post_text:
The Sunray robotics teams competed in the first tournament of the year last Saturday in Stinnett at WT High. There were 26 teams entered in this competition. The Sunray teams finished 9th, 13th, 16th, and 21st. We had a good day of learning and competed at a high level.

As a reminder, the last 5 state champions in robotics are from our district, and they were all 5 there at this competition.

The next Robot tournament is Dec. 7th at Dimmitt.

post_text: Mrs. Taylor‚Äôs art students enjoyed learning about the Theory of Composition in Photography from Mr. David Castillo on Thursday, September 26, 2019, during their regular art classes. Mr. Castillo is the Owner/Creative Director of Blue Barn Pictures, Inc. He also served as an instructor at the Digital Film Academy of New York, worked as a senior technical representative of Canon USA, and is a professional member of the Society of Motion Picture & Television Engineers. Mr. Castillo traveled to Sunray with Gayla Taylor, daughter of school board member, Shelby Taylor.

post_text: Mr. Harrison was selected along with 70 other Superintendent's nation wide to participate in National Superintendent's Summit as part of District Administration Leadership. District Administration Leadership is a national known leadership institute made up of educational leaders across the nation and it's main office is located in Florida. As a selected participants Mr. Harrison will be travel to Carlsbad, California in November and all expenses of the summit is covered by District Administration Leadership. It is Great Day to Be a Bobcat.

post_text:
2019 Accountability Update
The 2019 TEA A-F Accountability Ratings were released publically August 15, 2019. Sunray ISD finished with an overall ‚ÄúB‚Äù rating. Both Sunray High School and Sunray Middle School received an overall ‚ÄúB‚Äù rating, and Sunray Elementary School received an overall ‚ÄúC‚Äù rating. We are proud of all the hard work and dedication the Sunray ISD staff and students put in for the 2018-2019 school year. We are looking forward to an even better 2019-2020 school year!
It‚Äôs always a GREAT day to be a BOBCAT!
